package com.example.myapp;

import android.content.Context;
import android.content.Intent;
import android.os.Bundle;
import androidx.appcompat.app.AppCompatActivity;

public class SplashScreenActivity extends AppCompatActivity {

    @Override
    protected void onCreate(Bundle savedInstanceState) {
        super.onCreate(savedInstanceState);
        setContentView(R.layout.activity_splash_screen);

        // Wait for 3 seconds
        try {
            Thread.sleep(3000);
        } catch (InterruptedException e) {
            e.printStackTrace();
        }

        // Start the main activity
        Intent intent = new Intent(this, MainActivity.class);
        startActivity(intent);
        finish();
    }
}

The code above is an example of a splash screen activity in Android using Java. Here's a breakdown of what it does:

1. `setContentView(R.layout.activity_splash_screen)`: This sets the content view of the activity to the layout file `activity_splash_screen.xml`.
2. `Thread.sleep(3000)`: This line of code makes the activity wait for 3 seconds before moving on to the next step.
3. `startActivity(intent)`: This line of code starts the main activity (in this case, `MainActivity.class`) and passes the intent to it.
4. `finish()`: This line of code finishes the splash screen activity, which means that it will no longer be visible to the user.

To use this code in your project, you will need to create a new activity in your Android project and copy the code into it. You will also need to create a layout file for the splash screen (e.g. `activity_splash_screen.xml`) and add the necessary components to it (e.g. a logo, a progress bar, etc.).

Here are some tips for implementing a splash screen in your Android app:

1. Keep it short: A splash screen should only be displayed for a few seconds before the user is taken to the main activity.
2. Make it visually appealing: The splash screen should be visually appealing and reflect the style of your app.
3. Provide feedback: The splash screen should provide feedback to the user, such as a progress bar or a spinning wheel, to let them know that the app is loading.
4. Be careful with timing: Make sure that the splash screen is displayed for the correct amount of time. If it is displayed for too long, it can be frustrating for the user.
5. Test it thoroughly: Test the splash screen thoroughly to make sure that it works as expected and that it does not cause any issues with the rest of the app.

